\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy is written to serve two audiences simultaneously:
 ECIO personnel and internal auditors who read it within the full context of the ECIO Policy Manual,
 and external reviewers —
 including the Nevada state cyber defense office —
 who may review it as a standalone document.
 Where this policy references concepts,
 roles,
 or procedures whose authoritative definitions reside in other policies,
 it states the operative substance in plain language sufficient for an external reader and cites the authoritative source.
 Those plain-language statements are incorporative and do not constitute independent definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The postmortem review is the Lessons Learned phase of the ECIO cybersecurity incident response lifecycle.
 Its purpose is to produce a structured,
 documented assessment of the Department's response to a cybersecurity incident —
 what happened,
 what worked,
 what failed,
 and what must change.
 Postmortem findings feed back into the Department's governance,
 risk,
 and improvement frameworks to strengthen the Department's posture for the next incident.
 This feedback loop implements NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 IR-4 (Incident Handling),
 which requires that lessons learned from ongoing incident handling activities be incorporated into incident response procedures,
 training,
 and testing,
 and aligns with NIST CSF 2.0:
 ID.IM-01 (Improvements Identified from Evaluations) and NIST CSF 2.0:
 ID.IM-03 (Improvements Identified from Execution of Operational Processes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy is distinct from the Problem Management process governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Problem Management Policy),
 which applies to operational incidents.
 Cybersecurity incident postmortems are exclusively governed by this policy.
 The jurisdictional boundary between the two is addressed in Section 6.7.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Mandatory Postmortem Trigger
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Every cybersecurity incident declared under Chapter 4 authority shall receive a postmortem review under this policy.
 There are no severity-based exclusions and no deferral provisions.
 An incident that warranted declaration warrants documentation of how the Department responded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Incident Commander shall trigger the postmortem review as a precondition of Operational Handback under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Recovery Operations and Restoration Prioritization).
 The trigger shall be documented in the incident work order Notes and the Chapter 4 checklist at the time it is made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Postmortem Leadership and Separation of Duties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The person who commanded the incident response shall not lead the review of that response.
 This separation ensures that the postmortem review is conducted with independence from the operational decisions under examination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
When the Incident Commander was the IT Director
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall serve as Postmortem Lead.
 The IT Director shall participate in the postmortem meeting as a mandatory attendee.
 The IT Director retains final approval authority over the completed internal postmortem report,
 but shall not direct the investigation,
 suppress findings,
 or direct modifications to the Postmortem Lead's factual findings.
 The IT Director may add a written response or addendum to the final report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
When the Incident Commander was not the IT Director
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall serve as Postmortem Lead.
 The Incident Commander shall participate in the postmortem meeting as a mandatory attendee.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Postmortem Lead shall schedule the postmortem meeting,
 conducting the structured review,
 preparing the internal postmortem report,
 and presenting findings and recommended routing dispositions to the IT Director for approval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Postmortem Meeting and Completion Timeline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Postmortem Meeting
\series default
:
 The Postmortem Lead shall convene the postmortem meeting within five (5) business days of the Operational Handback declaration.
 The meeting is a structured debrief conducted while operational memory is fresh.
 All Information Operations personnel who participated in the incident response shall attend unless excused by the Postmortem Lead.
 The Postmortem Lead shall document attendance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Internal Postmortem Report
\series default
:
 The Postmortem Lead shall complete the internal postmortem report within ten (10) business days of the Operational Handback declaration.
 The IT Director shall review and approve the completed report.
 IT Director approval constitutes finalization of the internal report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
External Postmortem Derivative
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall prepare the external (redacted) postmortem derivative within five (5) business days of IT Director approval of the internal report.
 The IT Director shall review and approve the external derivative prior to any distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Internal Postmortem Report Content
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The internal postmortem report is the authoritative record of the Department's review of its response to a cybersecurity incident.
 The report shall be documented in the System of Engagement and shall include,
 at minimum,
 the following content:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Summary
\series default
:
 Incident type (Layer 1 category),
 severity classification,
 CJI involvement determination,
 declaration authority and declaring party,
 Incident Commander designation,
 and a narrative description of the incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Reconstructed Incident Timeline
\series default
:
 A chronological reconstruction of the incident from initial detection or report through Operational Handback.
 Each timeline entry shall be marked as 
\series bold
Known
\series default
 (confirmed by evidence —
 system logs,
 work order timestamps,
 forensic captures,
 or other documentary evidence) or 
\series bold
Suspected
\series default
 (assessed based on professional judgment where contemporaneous technical evidence —
 system logs,
 forensic captures,
 or work order timestamps —
 is unavailable,
 incomplete,
 or inconclusive).
 The Known/Suspected distinction shall be applied at the entry level,
 not as a blanket classification for the timeline as a whole.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Communication Record
\series default
:
 The communication data package compiled by the Assistant IT Director under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 including internal status updates,
 external notifications,
 partner engagement records,
 legal review metadata,
 and media communications.
 Data protection controls appropriate to the classification of the information under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Data Governance and Classification Policy) shall be applied to the communication record within the postmortem report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
False Positive Documentation
\series default
:
 When a false positive determination was made during the incident under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Eradication Procedures and Scenario Guides),
 including any documentation of the justification for original eradication actions,
 the Postmortem Lead shall incorporate that documentation into the report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Root Cause Analysis
\series default
:
 The Postmortem Lead's assessment of the root cause of the incident.
 Where root cause cannot be determined,
 the report shall state the basis for the indetermination and identify any investigative avenues that remain open.
 Root cause analysis in this context addresses why the incident occurred and why it was not prevented or detected sooner.
 It does not replace the operational root cause investigation function governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 for service failures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Phase-by-Phase Review
\series default
:
 A structured assessment of the Department's performance across each lifecycle phase that was activated during the incident (Identification,
 Containment,
 Eradication,
 Recovery,
 and Communication).
 For each phase,
 the Postmortem Lead shall document what worked effectively,
 what did not work effectively,
 and specific observations or recommendations for improvement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Findings and Routing Dispositions
\series default
:
 Each actionable finding shall be documented with a recommended routing disposition in accordance with Section 6.6.
 The IT Director shall approve the routing disposition for each finding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Postmortem Meeting Attendance Record
\series default
:
 A record of all personnel who attended the postmortem meeting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Draft Findings Preservation
\series default
:
 The Postmortem Lead's draft findings —
 including draft routing recommendations,
 working notes,
 and the draft report —
 shall be preserved as a permanent attachment to the postmortem record in the System of Engagement.
 The draft attachment shall not be modified after the IT Director approves the final internal report.
 This preservation requirement applies regardless of whether the IT Director modifies,
 supplements,
 or adds an addendum to the final report.
 The System of Engagement revision history provides the system-generated,
 tamper-evident audit trail confirming the sequence of drafts and approvals.
\end_layout

